segments.text: Debbie Parks interviewing Mr. Charles W. Crawford March 24, 1983 for the History of College Station Project at Mr. Crawford's house.
Alright, I'd like to start with some background on yourself.
Where were you born?
I was born in Benchley, Texas, about ten miles north of Brownsville.
Oh, that's right.
I've seen it as I've driven.
Well, are your parents from that same area?
Well, my mother was a Brownsville County girl.
My father was an M.D.
At that time, he was practicing medicine in Wellborn, Texas.
And he and my mother met, and they were married here in Brownsville County.
And so your father was a doctor then?
Yes.
Well, I bet there weren't that many doctors in his time.
Well, no, there weren't very many doctors at that time.
He was a son of an old pioneer in Texas who came to Texas in 1833 and said he felt that he won his Texas citizenship by fighting in the Battle of Harrisburg and the Battle of San Jacinto.
So your grandfather fought in the Texas Revolution?
Yes, the Texas Revolution.
Oh, that's wonderful.
What kind of education did you receive?
I went to country school in Harvey, Texas, and then I came into Bryan and went one year to Bryan Baptist Academy, and then I went
Next year I went to Bryan High School and finished my high school diploma in Bryan.
Then I came to Texas A&M and graduated from mechanical engineering in June 24, 1919.
That was a class that almost wasn't.
Because of the war?
Because of the war.
We started out with 600 students.
in the freshman class and wound up with 57.
Oh, no.
Well, were you in World War I then?
I was in the service a very short time, about three months.
Okay, after you got your bachelor's, then you must have gone on and...
I did.
I went on and got my master's degree.
In the fall of 1919, I had gone to work for
during the summer for the city of Port Arthur.
And I worked as an instrument man setting levels on some drainage project down in Port Arthur.
And in the fall, Professor Fermier, head of Mechanical Engineering Department, wired and offered me a job.
And since my mother and there were two younger children still in Bryan,
And I felt that they needed me.
I accepted the job as an instructor at Texas A&M, but really didn't expect to stay here more than a year or two.
But it turned out to be 46 years.
Well, can you tell me how it developed, what you became later in the department?
My whole career more or less happened.
It wasn't planned.
I came back to A&M, started teaching, and I found that I liked teaching.
And the first sommelier seemed to like me and think that I was doing a good job.
And so I continued to teach, and I gradually did graduate work while I was teaching.
It was about 1929, though, before I actually finished my master's degree.
But later on, you became the head of the department.
Well, as the years went along, I was advanced from assistant professor, associate professor, and then professor.
And in the fall of 1919, no, I take you back.
I didn't mean the fall of 1919.
Fall of 1927, Professor Cramier died.
long about, I believe it was the 27th of December.
And I continued to teach, and a man by the name of Bliss, Professor W.D.
Bliss, came in as head of the department.
And he was a former professor at Lafayette, head of the mechanical and chemical engineering department at Lafayette.
I can't think of the name of the school now.
Not Lafayette.
Is it Tulane?
No, it was up in Indiana.
Oh, it's Indiana.
But anyway, he had business interests and the Depression came on and he felt that he had to go back to his business up there.
And so when he left, why?
I was made head of the department.
Is that 1929?
And how long were you head of the department?
Until 1957.
No, yes, I believe that's right.
And then in 1957, I was made associate dean and remained in that position until 1962.
In 1962, I had reached the age
of 65 and they sent me back to the department and I taught three more years I believe and finally retired in 1965.
Well I was reading in your book about the early history of the A&M College and can you tell me about
Who owned the land that the college was established on and how the college came to be located where it is?
One of the chief men who influenced the location of A&M where it is today was named Harvey Mitchell.
And Harvey Mitchell was an old pioneer in this area and he owned a part of this land, but a Mrs. Rector owned part of it and one or two other people.
But Harvey Mitchell was instrumental in getting the titles and purchasing the land to donate to A&M for its establishment.
So he donated the land to the ?
Well, the people that gave the land, I'm not sure it was entirely a donation, but I think it was.
And there was three different plots of land.
I think he owned one.
Ms. Rector owned one.
I don't remember who owned the other.
But between those three, they gave the major portion of the land for A&M.
Did these people live in Bryan?
Live in Bryan, yes.
At this time, College Station was five miles out in the country, just out in the bleak open wilds.
no houses around in this area at all.
It wasn't anything, is that right?
No, plain open land.
Okay, so when A&M was established and you had the land around the college that later becomes College Station, was it still just open land?
What was there, if anything?
It was nothing here, but the commission that was appointed by

The governor, after the legislature had passed the bill creating A&M, was made up of three men, and they came over and surveyed the land, looked it over, and I understand that the local citizens gave them quite a big party.
Oh, really?
And they established A&M, or rather chose a site for it, and then
They were allowed such a very little time by the legislature under the laws to choose a location and employ an architect to plan the buildings.
And then they were supposed to get the buildings built and started within 90 days.
It was actually about three years before it actually happened that way.
Well, those things don't happen fast.
No, they sure don't.
So when the A&M wasn't established, then this land was fields and prairies.
Was it used for farmland?
It was open range.
It was just open farmland.
Were you aware of any Czech settlement in this area?
I find a lot of Czechoslovakian names in this area.
No.
I don't think there was any actual settlement.
group of people living around within any closer than Bryan, which was nearly five miles away.
Did you live on campus housing?
I'm aware that the campus had housing for professors.
Did you live in that housing?
I lived on the campus several years.
The house that I lived in originally was

up across the street from the post office and then it was moved down in the what we called the pecan orchard at that time and the pecan orchard was right next to the ASC building which is on the corner of the campus near the railroad at the present time.
The ASC building?
It was Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation.
They've changed the name of it a time or two, but I don't know exactly what the present name is.
So the house you lived in was moved to the Pecan?
Pecan Orchard, yeah.
And was that considered off campus?
No, it was on the campus, still on the campus.
Well, about how many houses were on campus for professors?
It'd be a guess if I were to say 25 would be, I don't know, that wouldn't be accurate at all, but that's about what I... Well, just a round figure is what I would say.
Well, did certain houses, like only professors rent certain houses?
Well, they were somewhat on the basis of seniority.
They had the houses for the presidents,
which was built for L.S.
Ross when he was president of A&M.
And then they had the houses for the deans and had houses for the full professors and the heads of departments.
And that was more or less when you became eligible for one.
The rents were very nominal.
Oh, so it was...
Very nominal.
I think I paid $15 to $20 a month for the house that I lived in.
I wish I could pay that.
So basically, around A&M, the community in its early days...
There was no community around A&M for many years.
It was on campus.
It was on the campus.
Well, could the university provide all your needs, such as the utilities and the water and the sewer?
They provided, yes, the electricity.
and the water and the sewer service.
Could you describe the roads or the transportation system around A&M?
Well the road coming from Bryan was considered a pretty good road.
It was gravel and it wound out from Bryan and came up by the F&B station near the
northwest corner area and then came on down what's now known as Wellborn Road into College Station.
That was a gravel road and considered a pretty fair road at that time.
So the only road to Bryan was where the Wellborn Highway is now?
That's right.
It's along by the railroad until it got up to the F&B Station and then veered off into
the road that now leads into Bryan.
Is that South College?
Are you talking about South College?
Yes, South College Avenue.
Okay.
What was Jersey or Texas 6 like?
Was it just a... What was what?
Jersey, you know where Jersey Street is?
Yes, that was one of the streets.
When the campus began to build up, and that was in, along about 19...
the area south of the college began to build up, and Jersey Street was one of the new streets in that near addition.
That addition was the first individual housing that was built around, adjacent to the campus.
It happened in the south?
Yes.
Were there any houses in the north, around Northgate area?
There were just a few houses that were up where we called the North Gate, and that's the present North Gate area.
But there were very, I would say that there were not more than 10 or 12 houses, 15 houses in that whole area, north campus.
What was Highway 6, our present Texas Avenue, what was that like?
Highway 6 didn't come in for a good many years later.
See, that was the backside of the campus.
Oh, it's the main entrance now.
Yes, but the main entrance to the campus was down at the railroad station, and there were two railroad stations, one for the
H&TC Railroad, Southern Pacific, and the other for INGN.
And that was considered the front of the campus.
And from where the present administration building, system administration building, out to the present Highway 6 was just all pasture.
That was considered the back pasture.
There was a road leading up from the northwest side of the campus, which is now, I believe, University Avenue, goes out by the north gate and went down out to the present Highway 6.
And that Highway 6 was just a dirt road
And that was called Sulphur Springs Road.
The one that is University today?
Yeah.
Is Sulphur Springs?
Yes.
And was it just a dirt road?
Or was Texas City?
The road came out from Bryan, out that way, and led on down.
to the south and west parallel pretty well where the present Highway 6 goes out to the Rock Prairie area.
And then Sulphur Springs Road veered off left and went down into the Navasad Bottom and went to Sulphur Springs.
That was just a dirt road.
I'm not sure where Sulphur Springs is.
Where is that?
Is it closer to Bryan or headed out?
I believe at the present time the old Sulphur Springs Road is, I can't think of the street now, I can't think of the street, the name, it's between here and Bryan.
I believe it's still called Sulphur Springs Road.
Uh-huh, there is one.
So this street veered off to that area.

Well, it paralleled President Highway, uh, Railroad, uh, President Railroad, but it was about a mile further northeast than the President from the, well, at that time that was Sulphur Springs Road, which led down into the country area out in the south,
southeast corner of the present campus.
And the present Texas 6 was just a dirt road, if anything.
Yes.
That road went on down to Wellborn and went on down to Navasota and went through the Brazos Bottom area and came into Navasota about a mile this side of Navasota, which turned
left when you're going down and went across the Navasota River Bridge.
That's the present Navasota River Bridge, which crossed over the railroad.
Oh, I see.
Highway 6 was finally continued on up to College Station after that former road was still, I think, still used but was practically abandoned.
Oh, is that right?
Do you remember the trolley line?
Oh yes, I rode that trolley many times.
Where did that run?
How was that?
It came right through my house here.
Oh, did it?
Actually, it came out from Ryan to what's called Hillcrest.
And then Hillcrest, the trolley came on down and crossed this little branch out here.
just where it became Cabot Avenue.

And you see, when it got to this point, to the point right down, just at the present time, it's just this side of that Catholic corner, and crossed the branch, and came right over here, and went into the campus right in from here about
about where Nagel is at the present time.
The street Nagel is.
Actually, it went into campus a little bit further west than that.
Well, when did they stop using the trolley?
I don't remember the date, but it was, I expect it must have been
I can remember when I wrote it in 1930.
Oh, that late?
Excuse me.
Were you living in a campus house when the board of directors ordered people to move off campus, ordered people to find houses in the area surrounding A&M?
I believe I was.
What did you do?
Did you buy one of the houses and move it?
To tell you the truth, I can't quite recall when that was.
Oh yes, I moved to Bryan.
I moved to Bryan after I got married, which was about 1926.
Then in 26, I lived in that location until I was made head of department.
That's when I moved to campus.
And I simply can't recall when I
moved off the campus.
Oh yes, I did.
I moved to another house on the campus, which was down by the old swimming pool, and lived in that house for several years.
And then about 19... Can't seem to get my dates very clear in there.
moved off the campus and lived off the campus a year before I built a house up on the hill in front of College Station.
That big two-story house up on the hill there was my home where I built it.
In which area though?
It's right out in front of the campus, about half a mile off the campus, up on the hill.
It's on, is it at Eastgate?
Across Highway 6.
Oh, it's at Eastgate.
Yeah, Eastgate.
And I built that house in 19...
I believe it was 40, a year after I moved off campus.
Was that in College Hills Estate that you built your house?
Well, it was part of College Hills Estate, yes.
I believe that's what they called it.
Okay, do you remember the public school system that was on campus for a while?
Do you remember that at all?
Yes, I remember the building.
It was a stucco, two-story stucco building over in the area where the
core area now is.
It's really not quite, it's almost where the road, the street coming down by the MSC now makes that bend right at the area that houses the core.
And that's where the school?
Yes, that's where the school building was.
Did any professors at A&M volunteer their time and teach there?
I think maybe that there was a little bit of that, but Mr. George Wilcox was superintendent of that school and was a good one too.
And they had a real good school for the time and they had full-time teachers.
I don't remember.
I remember the names of one or two, but
Mr. Wilcox I remember very distinctly because he's such a fine person.
Is he dead now?
Yes, he's been dead a good many years.
When your children went to school, did they go to the one that was on Jersey Street or did they go on campus?
I had one daughter and she was born while we were living on the campus and

While we were living on the campus, she grew up to enter school, but by that time they had organized President College Station School, Independent School District, and she went to that school for one or two years, and then she went to Bryan for several years, and finally,
while we were living up on the hill, why she went to Bryan and graduated from Bryan High School.
Is there any reason why she went to Bryan rather than the College Station School?
I don't really remember any.
We felt like that Bryan was an older school system and better established.
I guess I had gone there.
That might have influenced me some.
Can you remember what, before it became a city in the 30s and the 40s, can you remember what College Station looked like physically?
Any commercial developments?
There were very little commercial developments.
There was one or two stores at the north gate and there wasn't anything on the east gate and there was little development.

that was built across from the campus on the southwest corner of the campus, south corner, you might say, of the campus, there were about 10 or 12 of those project houses, which were two-story wooden frame buildings in which the men were allowed to live and they brought most of their food from the farms
And they had those, some of them had cows, brought cows and chickens.
And Dan Russell was the man who was the head of the project houses.
He was a graduate of Baylor University and was down here for many years as head of rural sociology department.
And there was a small community area built up
right along in there in the early 30s, which was just south of the campus, which was along where there was one or two stores, one or two filling stations.
This happened because of the project housing?
Well, this was just off the campus.
The project houses were on the campus.
Oh, I see.
Okay.
The American Legion built a little housing, well, built a two-story building in there
I believe it was two story, I'm not sure of that.
But anyway, the American Legion sponsored that and built that house to help the students who were members of the, what?
American Legion?
No, it wasn't the American Legion.
It was, I can't think of the name of it, connected with Masonic Lodge.
Not the Masons?
Yeah.
I don't remember the name of the organization, but they built the houses because housing was so badly needed.
These were for students, right?
Yes, they were for students.
And you said to, that's on the southwest corner of campus?
Yes.
And then you said off of campus in the south, a rural community?
That was across the present highway.
Oh.
Well, the Welburn Road runs parallel to the railroad.
This is at right angles, crosses just beyond the campus, now goes out to the airport.
Okay.
That's the main road that goes from the President, Texas Avenue, right across the edge of the campus and goes on out to the airport.
It was just across the road there that had this little
commercial development.
Okay.
I would like to talk about the incorporation of College Station, if you remember that.
Do you remember when it was incorporated in 39 and... Well, a real good friend of mine, professor of mathematics, Dr. John Binney, was, I believe, the first
mayor of College Station and he was mayor for several years until Professor Ernest Langford became mayor and after he became mayor he was mayor for about 20 years.
That's right.
And he taught me when I was a freshman at A&M.
Mr. Langford did?
Mr. Langford did.
He was a very good friend of mine.
Well, do you remember any of the reasons why the communities around A&M campus wanted to incorporate into a town?
At that time, the Bryan City Council decided that it was about time for them to incorporate and include College Station.
And the people who were at College Station didn't want to be incorporated in Bryan.
So they got together and organized the city of College Station to keep from being included in Bryan.
Why didn't they want to be included in Bryan?
They just wanted to be independent.
You kind of had a community around the college?
At that time, there were very few houses between Bryan and College Station.
Along the highway, there were just a few farmhouses.
I bet there weren't
were the dozen houses between here and the settlements of Bryan at that time.
And so they wanted to remain independent.
How did you feel?
Do you remember having any feelings one way or the other about College Station being incorporated?
Well, since I was living in Bryan and had lived in Bryan, I felt like it wouldn't be bad for Bryan to go ahead and incorporate College Station.
But a good many of my friends who
had never lived in Bryan, didn't feel that way.
But there's advantages to being incorporated into an older town.
I felt like there were some, especially the school system.
Plus your services and utilities.
Yeah.
At that time, Bryan City Power Plant supplied the electricity for A&M, except for what was on the campus.
A&M had its own power plant.
But the city of College Station, which grew up around here, was served by Bryan.
Oh.
The power plant.
Through, I think, REA lines.
No, at that time it was head of REA.
REA hadn't come in at that time.
Oh, OK.
So houses around were serviced by Bryan.
Yeah.
They had an agreement with Bryan.
Brian and them that if one had trouble that other ones could tie into the same system so they were could be connected in the case of emergency.
Do you remember like any publicizing meetings for incorporation or people who were active and well of course these are faculty members who would be active and pushing for
Well, most of the men who were active were members of the A&M faculty, like Dr. Benny and Mr. Lankford and Mr. Boyd.
Orrin Boyd, I believe, was not Orrin, but one of the Boyd men.
But other members of the community
Part of them were members of the faculty and part of them were one or two businessmen.
That were interesting.
Do you remember Mr., or maybe the doctor, McNew?
Very well.
McNew and I were good friends.
He, according to newspaper accounts, was very interested in seeing the college incorporated.
Yes.
He did some engineering work for the
the city of College Station.
I don't remember whether he was city engineer or not, but he had quite a bit of influence in that group.
Worked with them pretty closely.
Do you remember attending any meetings that talked about the pros and cons?
No, I actually don't.
I don't recall a thing in which I was involved.
Do you remember them, do you even recall them being held on campus?
I was wondering where they were held.
The meeting?
Uh-huh.
To talk about incorporation?
I really don't know.
You don't know.
Okay.
Do you happen to know how the board of directors felt about College Station incorporating the name?

agree or i think don't think there was any strong feeling but i think they agreed to it and felt maybe it would be to the best interest of the university for the college for them to be incorporated okay um i think we have a few minutes on this side excuse me i think i served

only two years or maybe four years but at that time four years at that time why Mr. Ewing Brown was a member of the council and Mr. Lloyd Smith a real good friend of mine was city manager and he had worked at the building and college utilities
for many years before he became the city manager of College Station.
At that time, the entire staff of the city of College Station consisted of Lloyd Smith, the city manager, and I believe one or two secretaries, and that was the whole group.
And practically none of these streets around College Station
paved at that time.
And they did some paving or black-topping, which was very thin coating of gravel and asphalt, but it did cut down on the dust and made pretty fast streets for College Station.
But at that time, they got out and graded the streets, put the asphalt on it, spread the gravel, and
had very little actual permanent construction, very light coating of topping.
OK.
In 1943 is when you became elected.
Why did you decide to run for office?
It seemed like at about that time that there was a change made
And I guess it was because I was pretty closely associated with Lloyd Smith and some of the men on the council, like Ernest Lankford.
And they were all good friends of mine.
It seemed at that time there just was an opening that I felt like I could fill.
And what ward did you represent?
I don't think we worked by wards at that time.
I think it was all just one group.
Mr. Langford was chairman, was the button mayor.
Lloyd Smith was the city manager.
Mr. Ewing Brown was, I believe he was a chemist, I'm not sure, on the campus.
And Reverend R.L.
Brown, who was the Baptist minister.
And there was one or two more men on that, but I've forgotten who they were.
Where did y'all meet and when?
At that time, they had just built that little building down next to the railroad, and we met there in that building.
And what nights?
Do you remember?
No, I don't remember.
Did you meet once a month or more often?
I think we met more often than that because we were more or less planning things that
We're very informal about it.
I don't imagine we kept a very complete set of minutes even.
It was very informal and just a matter of getting together and discussing our problems and deciding on what we'd better do, but it was very informal.
Very informal?
Yeah, very.
Did many citizens attend the meetings?
Did they come and talk about what they needed done?
I don't remember a single case in which any committee or group waited on us and wanted to have a presented problem.
Really?
So basically it was just the councilmen getting together and talking about what should be done?
That's right, as I remember it.
Okay.
At this point, do you remember how closely associated the council was to operations at A&M?
Did they confer a lot with the board of directors?
Very little.
I think that they knew what was going on, kept up with what was going on, but as far as the board of directors were concerned, there was very little
participation in any way with the College Station City Council.
Did College Station want to be able to be a city on its own and not depend on A&M?
Yes.
I think they felt that after the city was organized that they could go right ahead and operate independently of the College Station Board of Directors, A&M College Board of Directors.
But were the relationship pretty amiable, though?
Very amiable.
We seemed to have complete cooperation between the staff and the board of directors and the city council.
After all, nearly all those people were members of the A&M faculty.
